{
  "doc_id": "60403",
  "text": "The hinged total knee prosthesis coupled with a massive allograft of the distal end of the femur is an interesting treatment, even though it has been abandoned by some teams after several failures (infections, pseudoarthrosis and fractures). [CITATION_1] The survival curve of massive distal femur allografts is moderate to good, depending on the series (65% to 78% at 10 years). [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] This treatment restores bone stock that is useful for the future management of these young patients, avoids an amputation and allows early recovery (total weight-bearing at 3 months postoperatively).",
